<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="599" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1757,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1794,1820]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is a noun in apposition. It is derived from the name of the 
<typeStatus box="[1204,1252,1794,1820]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">type</typeStatus>
locality and is a Lowland Scot word for a hillside. It also links to George Wilson, noted in the Australian sugarcane industry for his broad Scottish accent, and who is commemorated in the other species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="599" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1757,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1901,1928]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[605,653,1902,1928]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">type</typeStatus>
locality in dry-tropical open forest in the southern Einasleigh Uplands west of Townsville (
<figureCitation box="[379,447,1937,1964]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1020,1045]" captionTargetBox="[314,1274,344,994]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[314,1274,344,994]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of Hypolepida species: blue triangle, H. wilsoni Britton, 1978; red star, H. braes Allsopp, new species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677951" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677951/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1757,2036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,390,1973,2000]" pageId="4" pageNumber="599">Natural history.</emphasis>
Adult males were flying during November early in the morning after rain the previous evening, but only one was collected (C. Lambkin, personal communication).
</paragraph>
